    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26a.26-28_0001"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Neihardt Collection</note>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">26</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        225 Willard Way, Ithaca, <hi rend="caps">N.Y.</hi>
                        April 20, 1958
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Dear John: -</salute></opener> <p>We have thought so much during the past twenty four hours of you, and of Alice, the other children, and of the little girls in this, your dark hour. And I have gone over in my mind those visits to your home when all was happiness there.</p>
                
                <p>How well I recall the light shining from Mrs. Neihardt's eyes, the glow of an illuminated soul. She had found love and beauty in her life, and they made all her days glad. I shall never forget the deep tenderness with with which she spoke of you and your poetry. I remember, too, that you told me once that love grows better with time because that is its nature. And so I have thought of that bond between you two, once the green of April, as touched by the the red and gold of sunset.</p>
                
                <p>Nothing of the substance of her life, nothing of what she meant to you, and of what you meant to her, will pass. All<del/> is now fixed for eternity. Her going was the law of life. She followed the way taken by all living
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26a.26-28_0002"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">27</fw>
                    
                    things from the very beginning. And now she has become a part of that "other world" of which she spoke so naturally.</p>
                
                <p>Yet, though you recognize this truth, you are sad and lonely, as indeed we all are when a loved one passes to the other side, leaving us on the brink of the void between the here and the here after. Bur know that if she could speak, she would tell you to carry one, and to give of yourself as long as you can.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>With all our understanding and affection, dear, dear, friend,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Slade</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
            
            
